SUMMARY:Half Day Fridays at Sandy Hook
DESCRIPTION:Spring migration at the hook; we may see a wide range of species from wading birds to raptors to songbirds at this regional hotspot. \nSpring birding at the hook for migrants. The wide variety of habitats here ensures a good diversity of bird species from herons and egrets to shorebirds\, hawks\, and songbirds. Every week is different as we watch spring migration unfold. Be prepared for a fair amount of walking over flat and sometimes sandy terrain. Meet at parking lot B by the bathrooms. Led by Scott Barnes\, Linda Mack\, Carole Hughes\, and other associate naturalists. \nWEATHER & TRANSPORTATION: Please arrive at the appointed time. Be sure to check the forecast in advance and dress in layers appropriate for prevailing weather conditions. We sometimes bird in the rain\, so bring rain gear if warranted. Transportation during the field trip is by private vehicle (be sure you have enough gas). Most trips involve some amount of walking\, sometimes through muddy or sandy terrain. \nLOCATION: Meet at Parking Lot B\, about halfway down the lot by the bathrooms \nPRE-REGISTRATION REQUIRED \nCOST: $25 Members\, $30 Non-members \nCANCELLATION: NJA/CMBO programs require a minimum number of registrants to run\, five days in advance of the start of the tour but are seldom cancelled. If we do cancel\, due to lack of participation\, severe weather\, or unforeseen circumstances\, we notify all participants in advance\, and all are eligible for a full credit or refund. Participants may cancel without penalty if greater than 30 days in advance. Cancellations 10 to 30 days in advance may be subject to a 25% service charge. No refunds or credits for cancellations less than ten days in advance unless due to health emergencies. \nREGISTER HERE
URL:https://njaudubon.org/event/half-day-fridays-at-sandy-hook-48/
LOCATION:Sandy Hook – Lot B\, Hartshorne Drive\, Sandy Hook\, NJ\, 07732\, United States
CATEGORIES:All Things Birds,Bird Walk,Birding
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://njaudubon.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/01/Sandy-Hook-Spring.jpeg
GEO:40.4071808233;-73.9782969352
